See the Laurentian Medici Library by Michelangelo in Florence|https://www.european-traveler.com/italy/see-the-laurentian-medici-library-by-michelangelo-in-florence/|Biblioteca Medicea Laurenziana is the Medici library designed by Michelangelo in the San Lorenzo complex in  ...    The Laurentian Medici Library (Biblioteca Medicea Laurenziana) is a major library in Florence. For tourists, the main  ...    Access is via a vestibule with a monumental stone staircase, which Michelangelo originally intended to be walnut.  ...    and mostly designed by Michelangelo. The plutei (wooden reading benches) served both as reading bookstands and to house the large codices. These large codices were chained physically to the plutei — readers had to change seats to read a different book. The Medicis loved good ceilings, and this fine ceiling is no exception. It was carved from lime wood by Giovan Battista del Tasso to Michelangelo’s designs. The windows are probably by Flemish artisans to designs by Vasari, while the  ...    The Medicis opened the library to scholars in 1571, and it remains a major functioning library. The collection includes around 11,000
Michelangelo's Laurentian Library - ArtTrav|https://www.arttrav.com/florence/laurentian-library/|Laurentian Library, part of the complex of the Basilica of San Lorenzo, was part of Pope Clement VII’s plan to  ...    period. Below the windows are the custom made reading benches called plutei, consisting of a bench, a shelf and an angled book holding part. The 3000 or so books of the Medici collection were recovered on the occasion of the opening of the library with leather jackets sporting the Medici coats of arms. The books were chained to the furniture, so you went to read it where it was stored. Books were organized by thematic section, and a list of what each bench contained was posted on the exterior of the row. This system was in use until the 19th century, when the collection was moved out of the historic space. Nowadays
