Sagrestia Nuova by Michelangelo - TheHistoryOfArt.org|https://www.thehistoryofart.org/michelangelo/sagrestia-nuova/|# Sagrestia Nuova  Michelangelo  ...    architect. While Michelangelo would sculpt and paint throughout his long career, it was after his work on the Sistine  ...    Like his paintings and sculptures, Michelangelo's designs are just as impressive. His first major architecture work was the Sagrestia Nuova in Florence.  ...    Vecchia (Old Sacristy). The Sagrestia Nuova sits across from Brunelleschi's Sagrestia Vecchia in the San Lorenzo. The design of each Sacristy is very similar. The New Sacristy is a cubic space that is topped with a decorative dome that has sunken decorative panels. The interior walls are an early example of Renaissance Mannerism. The use of distortion in both scale and perspective makes the architectural parts of the structure appear impossible thereby creating a sense of'suspense and tension'. In his design, Michelangelo makes use of grey sandstone (pietra serena) pilaster elements to give the appearance of supporting columns on each of the corners. He also used
